==English==

====Etymology====
From [[After]] + math (From [[w:Old English language|Anglo-Saxon]][[Category:Anglo-Saxon derivations]] m;  akin to m&macr;wan (meaning ''to mow''), [[w:German language|German]][[Category:German derivations]] [[mahd]] math. See [[mow]] & compare with [[math]], [[maths]] (From [[mathematics]]))

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-aftermath.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
'''aftermath'''

#(Obsolete) A second mowing; the grass which grows after the first crop of hay in the same season. 
#Hence; that which happens after, that which [[follow]]s. Has a strongly negative connotation in most contexts, implying a preceding [[catastrophe]].
#:''In contrast to most projections of the '''aftermath''' of nuclear war, in this there is no rioting or looting.''
